segments.text: Once we were paid, it's working at the mess hall, but we got our food.
You didn't get all your food, though.
You got thank yous.
That's where I remember we got our food.
And that was a big item.
Oh, sure.
That was a big item.
And the sacrifice that my family could make and did make, why?
Did they help out?
Oh, yes, they helped out.
Did your father help out?
helped out and was a great inspiration to me, because I knew they were sacrificing to keep my brother in the law school.
And I was able to find work, and he wasn't.
So it didn't bother me a bit in the world.
I wanted to do it.
And as I remember, I kept books on it.
It cost me about $1,600 to go through A&M for four years.
And I'm sure they contributed.
half a little more of it, and I made the rest.
What did you think of the living conditions then?
Of living conditions?
Well, of course, I ate it up.
I liked it.
I could see where I was going.
I thought I could see where I was going.
And I kept busy.
I went out to play basketball and my size and all I thought would be a help, but it conflicted with my work, studies, no question about it.
I let it conflict with my work, let's say it that way.
Whether it necessarily would or should or not, then I was taking a full course
It conflicted with my work, and I was getting along in basketball, let's just say it that way.
And one time we got our grades and I wasn't doing so well, and I got a letter, a note from Dean Bolton.
He wanted to talk to me.
So I went over and talked to Dean Baldwin.
He was head of the engineering department at that time.
Great old gentleman, great teacher, and a great philosopher, in my opinion.
He knew how to handle kids, boys.
He sat me down.
He talked to me for a long time about, asked me the same kind of questions, why I came to A&M and what I wanted out of A&M, this kind of thing.
And I told him.
And he said, well, now, did you finally ask me the question, did you come down here to play basketball or did you come down here to get an education?
Now, Kibble, I don't want you to make up your mind right now.
I want you to go think about this and come back and tell me in two or three days.
And so I did.
And I went back and told him that I came down
And he said, well, I'm so glad you made up your mind.
Now get about it.
Anyway, I can help you a while.
Let me know.
Otherwise, get about it.
Just start studying.
So I started studying.
And my junior year, I liked one great point of being qualified, you know, as outstanding student.
They called it qualification those days.
And my senior year, I mean, they called it
distinction, distinguished student.
And my senior year I had, as I remember, 17 grade points more than necessary to be a distinguished student.
My senior year I got all As.
That's fantastic.
Fantastic.
My junior year I got all As but one or two.
After the good dean convinced me that
that the education was there, and if you came down to get it, get after your boy.
And if you didn't, why?
I don't know what he had done if I had gone back and told him I wanted to play basketball.
He probably told me that the train leaves at 4.30 next afternoon and be on it.
But that didn't happen, and so I went ahead and graduated as a distinguished student in 1932.
I just took- Must have been awfully hard to get a job.
It was extremely hard to get a job.
And I was the first one in our class of structural engineers, what I took.
I'm a registered civil engineer, but I took structural engineering then and then.
Because I wanted to get into construction.
I didn't want to be a consultant engineer.
As such, I wanted to be out here under the building.
And being a builder, and so I took structural engineering.
thinking that that would better qualify me for the big picture of what I was trying to do.
And I believe there were eight or nine, eight of us in that class, in that group.
And I was the first one who got a job for seven months.
I got a job
working for Mr. P.O.B.
Montgomery, who was a Dallas building contractor who built the University of Texas.
I mean, that's where I went to work for him, down at the University of Texas building, the library, the present library, the present physics, and the present union building down there.
Those three buildings were in one contract, $1,750,000.
Were they federal funds?
I have no idea.
University of Texas funds, I presume.
Because they didn't have all that federal business then.
Oh, in 1932 they, oh, well in 1933 they did.
They started in 33 and 34, but true.
I don't know.
I wasn't interested in where the money's come from.
I was interested in the job, and I got a job down there as a laborer for 25 cents an hour.
I was a beautiful draftsman in those days, and
I kind of worked as a apprentice engineer in the office, the superintendent's office.
Those buildings were structural steel jobs.
And the structural steel would come out not fabricated exactly like the plans showed.
In other words, the rivet holes wouldn't line up.
and we might have to send a piece back to be either rebuilt or re-bored or something.
And I would do that job detailing on the job and send it back steel fabricated.
This was a kind of roustabout crew that I was in.
There were 10 of us, all civil engineers.
Now that I was making $0.25 an hour.
And Tethland had a master's of civil engineering.
He made $0.30 an hour.
So he was a crew chief.
And he was in the contracting business here for a long time, building contracting business here for a long time in Dallas.
We did roustabout work around the jobs.
measuring dirt, setting grades, checking material coming in, running errands for the superintendent, this kind of thing.
I used to go with him and watch him check the rivets to be sure they were tight rivets.
That's where I learned to know whether a rivet's tight or not and whether it's got to come out or not.
That's when I learned it in sophomore CE summer training where they have that field course on measuring dirt and running lines and grades and all.
But that's the first time I ever applied it was down there measuring dirt in excavations.
measuring field dirt and measuring crushed rock and this kind of thing.
We mixed all our own concrete on that job and we unloaded rock out of a gondola car with a number 10 scoop.
When we weren't doing some of this engineering, I was out there in a gondola car unloading crushed rock for two bits an hour.
But it's all relative.
It's a good job.
Like I say, I was the first one out of our group of eight structural engineers that got a job.
And I was thankful for it.
Every day I went through four, five, 600 people, men wanting jobs.
And believe you me, if you got a job, you go through that kind of a
environment getting to your job, it'll make you dig a better ditch faster and cleaner.
And it did me that.
Now let's go back for a minute here at the Corps.
Did you have a position of leadership in the Corps?
At A&M?
No.
No.
I was qualified, but I did not have a position of leadership in the A&M Corps.
What were some of the things that you liked and what were some of the things that you disliked about being in the Corps?
I liked every moment of it, and I didn't dislike one moment of it.
There wasn't anything at all?
I'm convinced that it made a man out of me.
Oh, fine.
OK.
So let's talk about in what ways then the Corps helped you.
What do you mean it made a man out of you?
It made a man out of me in that I learned to take discipline.
After my early training, I learned, I mean my parental training, I learned to take discipline from strangers.
And I learned to respect authority, meaning a corporal tell me something to do, and I'd do it.
A lieutenant tell me something to do, I'd do it.
And I liked the routine.

the demanding routine, and it was a demand of getting up and making your bed up, cleaning it up, cleaning yourself up, going down and answering a revelry call, and cleaning up your sophomore, your junior, your senior's rooms, and marching to breakfast, going to the classroom, marching to lunch, going to the classroom, marching, going to information for a retreat every night.
So you like the regimentation?
Well, I guess that's the way to put it.
I like the routine.
Yeah, the routine, okay.
If that's regimentation, well I like regimentation.
I enjoyed the fellowships.
Yeah, I would think so.
Of your colleagues?
The greatest friends I have were made at A&M.
And we'd be lifelong friends.
Why do you think that is?
Why do you think?
I've talked to many generals, and they said the same thing.
The greatest friends I met, I started our friendship at A&M.
Why do you think that is?
Going through the core from the time I got off of that train

early at 4 o'clock, 4.30 the first morning I was there and going up there and associating myself with two or three friends and then some strangers and becoming part of the group and going through the fellowship of the hazing and that was real fellowship in the final analysis.
It was me qualifying to
participate in being one of the fellows, being a good fish, if that's a good way to put it.
And by being a good fish, I established myself as being a good friend.
And all the way up the line, the core, I like to drill.
I like to work with the horses.

And I liked the competition that we got, and the horsemanship, and then the qualifications in the military sense of meaning, the gunner's qualification, and the number one qualification, and all those jobs.
I accomplished all of them, and to me it was very basic training.

The friendships that I made with A&M are indelibly imprinted in my mind and I could, I dare say I could go to any one of them today and ask them for the shirt off the back and they'd give it to me and vice versa.
The esprit de corps idea.
Esprit de corps was the outstanding thing that you leave A&M with.
Equally so with a good education.
This is the thing that distinguishes A&M against University of Texas engineering students, for instance.
Okay, let's talk about that now.
This is the thing.
I was convinced if I wanted to be an engineer, I should go to A&M to be an engineer because I wanted to stay in Texas.
If you want to be a lawyer, you ought to go to University of Texas because University of Texas lawyers run
our law business in this state.
If you want to be a doctor, you ought to go to Baylor or the University of Texas Medical School.
If you want to be an engineer, you ought to go to A&M.
And their ex-students or their status, if that's the way to put it,
has been long since established as a potential leader in the engineering world.
There are more engineers and leaders jobs today, A&M engineers, than any other school in this part of the country.
And my cousin convinced me of that
back in those days when I was formulating and convincing myself, confirming my convictions, that that's where I wanted to go to school.
And I don't regret one moment of it.
I think the basic understanding and fellowship of any A&M graduate is well worth all the trials and tribulations of going down there
in those days in the Corps and coming out of it.
Now, you became a general, which is a leader.
How did A&M or the Corps affect that?
Did it help you in some way become a leader?
Well, I'm sure it helped me in my analytical mind.
It helped me in the discipline of myself.
It helped me to
be able to lead men.
As a general officer, you have to be two things.
You have to be a leader and you have to be a capable administrator.
And A&M taught me both.
I can't get away from the indelible lessons that
that I got at A&M that I've used all the rest of my adult life.
Those things stay with you, become a part of you.
And to me, that's what A&M's all about.
Now, let's for a second here compare, for a minute, compare the officers of A&M with officers of our other so-called ROTC schools.
Would you compare those?
Well, yes, I certainly compared them with West Point.
And I've compared them with Oklahoma University, who had an artillery unit up there, OTC.
I've compared them with Purdue.
They had an ROTC unit, artillery unit there.
I've compared with Alabama.
They had an artillery unit there.
I think those were the three.
artillery units, and because I was so closely associated with the artillery, I couldn't help but be associated with those schools.
Sure.
Invariably, we tried to, I as an officer, and I'm sure all A&M officers tried to excel West Poners, because
I think if we could do it, we did do it, in that that was their job, and to me, my Army career was an extracurriculum activity.
When the Gauntlets were down, and the
very, life as I know it in our country was at stakes, meaning the safety of our country or the defense of our country was at stakes.
I was a true dyed-in-the-wool army officer and every every
every day was a challenge to me to excel and I did.
I excelled in showing up many West Pointers that they would have corresponding commands of mine and it was it was a real really it was a sometimes a detriment because a senior
What was the detriment?
My desire to be, to excel.
Oh, okay.
Because some very senior officers, meaning two and three and four-star generals, would hold me up as an example to West Pointers.
And that didn't help our relations at all.
No, I wouldn't think so.
I mean our admiration for one another at all.
I did it because I was going to excel irrespective of where I'd gone to college, and they were out there doing their daily work.
It was all a chore to them, and to me it was a challenge.
And so I saw it every day.
Nothing in the world gave me more pleasure than winning a competition over one of them.
and my artillery units did.
We won lots of competitions over them, and consistently got better ratings, and then one or two out of the four that we were associated with, you know, just free decor of the artillery.
Well, could you compare the officers of those institutions you talked about with the A&M officers?
The best way to compare them is to tell you the admiration that the very senior regular army officers held for the A&M Cardiff Blind, an A&M ROTC officer.
Invariably, they were given the responsibility above any other school, because the senior officers knew that the A&M officers were
Carry the ball, get the job done, period.
No question about it.
As versus some of the others.
A&M had a better basic training, I think.
They came out of A&M better equipped to do a better job.
And this is not the fault of Oklahoma University or Purdue or Alabama or any of the rest of them.
It's the excellence of Texas A&M.
Well, what about West Point?
Well, I don't know.
They don't teach the same thing as A&M teaches.
They don't indoctrinate their people at A&M, taught in those days.
That's what I'm talking about.
And I'm sure it's just, it's much better today.
Because A&M, you know, in those days was the outstanding college in our world.
And I'm sure they had problems that we got reflections of, but didn't know the
the details or weren't concerned with, let's say it that way.
But in later life, I got into a lot of those problems.
John Rutter was a very close friend of mine.
We were classmates.
And he and I were very close friends, as close as I guess he was to anybody.
And he would discuss his problems there with me.
Maybe as a trial balloon, I finally got convinced that that's what he was doing, is getting my opinion.
I'm sure he talked to a lot of people that same way.
But I can see that a lot of my recommendations were adopted that way, too.
And so I know he had problems just like everybody else does.
I credit the A&M Corps training to have qualified me and given me the desire and equipped me to do things I did in the Army, which were excelled.
OK, what about, let's move away from the Corps and the military aspect of A&M.
and move on to the academic.
You gave a little example of how you were prompted, we might say, to do better.
What did you think of the professors, the quality of the professors, back in the early 1930s at A&M?
Well, I would never criticize any of them, although I had some
very definite thoughts about them.
For instance, perhaps some of them were too old or too, I remember a very kind gentleman named, we nicknamed him, his name was Robert something Smith, and we called him Bobby Smith, taught calculus.
And I busted calculus.
Busted it the first time I took it because I didn't apply myself.
Nothing to worry about.
But anyway, I took it under him a second time and passed it.
But he didn't teach me the calculus that I think some of the others could have taught me, purely and simply because he was too old to teach.
I don't know his status.
I don't know his rank or anything about that.
But he would come in.
It was so methodical with him.
He'd come in and, gentlemen, the lesson today was
on page 22, 23, and down to paragraph 2 on 24.
He would start out with a problem and go right on across the board, never talk, never get out of a monotone, explaining the problems.
If there were three, he'd go around the board three times, and that's the end of the class.
That wasn't the kind of teaching that probably would have gotten the points over to me.
versus a teacher that would have been asking Kidwell and Jones and Smith and Babcock questions and kept us on our toes.
Some of the other instructors were outstanding, and I still remember their instruction over in the CE department.
Doc Grinter taught me structures, and he was outstanding.
Grinter?
Grinter.
How do you spell that?
I believe it's G-R-U-E-N-T-H-E-R, Grinter.
I'll look him up.
And another one, Sleepy Joe Stansted, Dr. Stansted.
I think he later headed the CE department.
I'll look him up, too.
He would come in, and he would give us a test every week.
And if you passed all those tests, or you passed his required number of those tests, you didn't have to take final exams.
And so you cram by the week, instead of cramming by the end of three and a half months, or four months, whenever it was.
I liked that method of teaching.
It got my lessons over to me better, let's say it that way, and that's what I have to judge it by.
I wouldn't criticize any of the instructors because I got an education.
Maybe I could have gotten a finer one by more sleepy Joe Sandstead than
more Dr. Grenners than I could fewer Dr. Bobby Smiths.
What about your colleagues as far as students, other corpsmen as far as students?
Were they good, bad, indifferent?
Did they help you or didn't that have much of an impact?
Did you think it was more individual?
It was more individual help.
The juniors in B Battery rode hard over you being at your desk from call to quarters, which I think was 7.30 to 9.45.
And you had a book in your hand, and you'd be looking at that book.
They came around and checked, theoretically, making sure that you were studying.
We couldn't be in our room playing dominoes or cards or watching, listening to radio.
They didn't have TV in those days, but listening to radio.
Or having a bull session.
You had to be studying.
The juniors ran.
That was their delegated responsibility as far as the company commander was concerned.
Because the company commander was judged based, among other things, on the academic standing of all of his company.
Sure.
Absolutely.
That was his method or their methods of making you study doing what was called a call to quarters, which was a study period from 7.30 or 7.15, something like that, till 9.45.
If I wanted to go to another hall, say I wanted to go over to Bazell and study with one of the men in my class on a problem that we had
were having, I had to go get permission to be out of my room.
From Mr.
Junior, it was checking that night.

Go to the first sergeant, he'd tell you, well, Sergeant Smith's checking tonight, or Sergeant Jones, or Sergeant somebody, and you'll tell him, if they thought you were sloughing off on them, they'd check up.
And if you didn't go to,
Jones' room over in Bazell Hall, and they caught you at it, you got ten licks with the board.
That's all it was to it.
And, you know, that took incentive out of goofing off real quick.
Taught honesty.
Taught honesty, that's right.
Now, I've heard in a number of interviews that A&M is more than just a college or a university or just an institution, but it's something special or unique.
What are your thoughts on that?
Certainly, it's unique in its own right.
But it's a spirit of the Corps that is indelibly impressed on your very life, or your philosophy of life, your attitude on life, your approach on people.
Today, you go in and introduce yourself.
You grab him with a hand, and you shake him with the same grasp that
you don't get from ex-students in SMU or Texas University or anywhere else.
You have the...
I don't want to say forwardness, but you have the self-satisfaction and self...
confidence of going on and saying, my name's Kidwell, and this is what I want to talk to you about.
Or how's the weather, and how are you getting along on this job, and you got a problem, I got a problem, how will you solve it?
With a full confidence of knowing that I'll be listened to and can work it out.
Sure.
Getting the job done.
Getting the job done.
I think that that self-confidence is as much a part of the things that taught me at A&M as anything.
The good dean did that and taught me that I could excel academically.
I'm sure that old Bull Nelson taught me that in our
ROTC work.
He was an old time infantry colonel and he was bull of the woods.
When we were down there, I'll never forget the funniest thing, if you could ask me this I'll tell it now and I can repeat it, was the funniest thing that happened at A&M.
Of course lots of funny things happen.
But we were living in Milner Hall at that time and

Some of the Hellraisers, if that's a good word, call it a good name for them, would get these railroad torpedoes, steal them from the SP when they go, when someone's on a train, and either put them between two bricks or put them on a piece of reinforced steel and drop them, point down or something, and they hit the concrete paving in the, I call it the wells, you know, the ventilation wells in Milner Hall.
It's on a figure eight design, and these interior wells have got concrete in them, and they drop them off second, third, fourth floor, and she'd blow off like a shotgun.
And they'd been dropping them for a month or something, like once a week or something, just to break monotony of so much studying.
And they're getting ready to have a board of directors meeting down there.

And the night before the board's meet the next day, Colonel Nelson came over, got a B battery out on the steps of Milner Hall, and he gave us a lecture on conduct while the board of directors was on the campus.
And he came out with a statement
any more of those goddamn torpedoes going off, I'll walk every one of you to Brazos.
And he hadn't dismissed us two minutes before, whoom, whoom, whoom.
And he came right back and he got our tactical officer, Captain Richards and Captain Richards,
and Lieutenant Paul, I believe was his name, Lieutenant Paul, and Captain Harry, Tom Harry.
And of course he said, now I told you, you're going to the Bradditch, so follow the battery out and walk to the Bradditch.
And so they fell the B battery out, called a roll.
The old Colonel Nelson was down there at the Brazos in his car when we got there, and he called a watch, called a roll.
And believe you me, when he spoke from in on out, we reacted.
But that was the first walk to the Brazos.
But he hadn't got any more.
No more of those.
Colt got the words out of his mouth, the whoom, whoom.
I mean, been in the Corps, you know.
Sure, absolutely.

Let's shift now, oh wait, before we shift to your military career, I should ask you if there's anything else about being at A&M or the Corps or academics or anything that you think we should discuss before we move on?
Was there any really, real important or very significant?
episode that happened that you'd like to discuss?
No.
That had an impact?
No.
I think the, of course, like I said, there's lots of funny things that happened, and you're not interested in funny things.
I think that the thing that got out of the core more than anything else was the discipline, the training to discipline, and the self-confidence that
I carried and the friendships that I made.
How about preparation for your military and civilian career?
Well, that's the discipline and all that you got.
Basically, I realized that the Army wanted, when I got in December of 48, they wanted people that they could
give a job and depend on to get the job done.
They wanted somebody to carry the ball.
And I had certainly learned that.
I learned when very early, and I don't remember what it is, I'm sure it was at A&M, somebody tell me to do something.
If I couldn't do it, I learned to go tell them I couldn't do it and why, and they said,
on doing some other way.
And maybe that's a good trait too, in that you recognize impossibilities.
Of course, like somebody said one time,
Harder things take a little while to do.
And impossible, well, that takes a little longer.
And sometimes you learn that and have to work at it harder.
But that's what the Army looked for.
And anybody that can give them that response can't help but go up in it.
They give you the responsibility, they give you the tools to do your job, and if you do the job, you're recognized for it.
And that was my whole experience in the Army.
A&M gave me the basic foundation, and I stayed active in the Army, I mean in the Reserves, meaning going to

two weeks summer active duty and going to, we called it troop schools in those days, going to once a night training during the week and doing correspondence work to keep up with Army changing tactical training and
Here in Dallas, we had the 407th Field Artillery Group, a reserve group.
And we went down every Thursday night.
And that became just a part of my life of going to troop school on Thursday night, as Sunday morning Sunday school and church is.
It's just something that I started doing when I was a bachelor and carried right into my married life.
My wife knew that on Thursday night they have early dinner, so I'll go to troop school at 7 o'clock.
And I got promoted to first lieutenant and then to captain.
I was a captain when I was called in the Army in 1940.
Yeah, well let's talk about your military career now.
Let's talk about the early reserves.
How did you become involved with the reserves?
Of course, the United States Army wasn't too interested in active duty personnel during the Depression.
How did you become involved with the reserves?
I became involved with them in that they had these reserve units in the major cities.
They had one in Dallas.
And Dallas is where I started to work.
And then I went to Austin, they had one there.
I was interested in equipping myself with current Army training purely and simply to prepare myself in the eventuality of the defense of our country.
They taught me that down at A&M.
And certainly, when you got down in the reserves, that's what they preached to you.
about patriotic preparedness promotes peace.
And the best defense is preparedness.
They taught that then and they haven't changed the philosophy one older today.
I'm convinced that that's correct and I've proved it out
Army career.
So you want to stay up, the reason why you became involved with the reserves is that you wanted to stay up on new artillery methods.
On new artillery methods and in doctrine so that if there was ever an occasion I would be qualified.
Okay.
When did you join your first reserve unit?
In May or June of 1932 when I got my commission.
Okay.
When I graduated day and in.
Okay, okay.
And can you tell us about the conditions?
And let me flip back through here and I'll give you the exact date.
These are chronologically in order now.
And I should have the appointing authority.
You were commissioned the 28th of May, 1932.
Here's my commission right here.
Yeah, that's correct.
As 2nd Lieutenant Field Artillery.
Yeah.
And the way that thing worked...
I went to these training schools, and when I finished my correspondence courses, they gave you a certificate of capacity as having qualified yourself for the promotion of the next grade.
And here's coming out of where they give you that
certificate and tell you that you're qualified for the next promotion.
